CMO is an HR communications solution that provides employee managers with automated tools that emphasize what is important to an employee. Managers are provided with proactive alerts when an employee or their declared family member(s) has a birthday, an anniversary, or a graduation ceremony. The alerts (triggered by dates provided by the employer) allow the managers the opportunity to formally offer use of an employee’s PTO balance for multi-day excused absences, offer a half-day in preparation for event planning, or perhaps an early release to provide the employee time to be both physically AND mentally present in their family’s important occasions. Sometimes, starting the conversation can remind an employee of important dates they may not have remembered! CMO assists employee managers with informing and conversing with an employee that they are due for a performance evaluation, constructive counseling, or they are in the window for an upcoming promotion. 

For the employee, they log in to a dashboard that reflects their PTO remaining balance and the ability to request PTO, the ability to update declared family member’s information, and a display that reflects the last time they were evaluated and the last time they were promoted and discuss these topics via official conversation / message with their employer. It’s important to note, this application IS NOT a replacement for face-to-face appointments with an employer and should not be used exclusively as the discussion medium for such important topics.

Most modern music productions utilize audio samples to elevate and achieve their sonic goals for their project song. Whether it is a piano melody, or a drum break, or a sound clip of cars passing by on a busy road, producers "chop up" these audio files in their DAWS(digital audio workstations) to isolate specific parts (loops) to inspire the main riff of a song or layer sounds on top of each other for a unique "one-shot" sound. Drum samples specifically, are very unique and are often made, collected, and traded amongst producers in packs (zip files) called "drumkits."

I work across three PCs, and every switch costs time: broken .env files, missing secrets, stale notes, and scattered prompts/snippets across password managers, bookmarks, Notion, and gists. That fragmentation creates config drift, avoidable bugs, and rework. Deadline was born from that pain.

Deadline is a web-based command center that keeps everything in one place: environment variables per workspace and per environment (Dev/Stg/Prod), a reusable library of prompt/code templates, and a curated hub of trusted documentation links. In a world of multi-environment setups and AI-assisted workflows, reuse and consistency matter more than ever. Deadline gives a fast, opinionated, least-privilege, auditable hub so I can move between machines without breaking flow—and ship with confidence.
